The Prague Stock Exchange went down at the end of the trade
The Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses after the rapid fall in the morning.
Transactions in the shares of the Czech Energy Enterprise (<0xC4><0x8C>EZ) accounted for almost half of the usual daily trading.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued its fall on Monday from the start of Tuesday’s trading, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the decline in Wall Street shares is behind the decline.
This is how the market reacts to the outcome of the U.S. House of Representatives’ vote, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Decrease in stocks in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic drop in stocks on Tuesday, although indicators eventually cancelled some of the losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock market index recorded a write-off of almost four percent in the course of trading, but later cancelled some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while the markets in Shanghai were closed.
Stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually the losses dropped to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange fell 3.6 percent, according to the index.
"The timing of the U.S. rescue operation is uncertain and will affect the world's financial markets," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Financial Council.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should start negotiations immediately and adopt a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens to make other countries feel the consequences of this.
The bloodbath of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was supposed to receive <0x24>700 billion (almost 12 trillion kroner).
The lawmakers ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
Bush said the plan would address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the economy as a whole.
On Monday, U.S. stocks went through a bloodbath and leading stock indices recorded the biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell nearly seven percent, the last time it fell was in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but as soon as it became clear that the proposal had not been adopted in the House of Representatives, the index began to fall freely.
Congress Retreats: US Government Can Pump <0x24>700 Billion in Banks
The Supreme Leaders of the US Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the agreement and financial assistance to the US financial system.
This will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in negotiations to approve the rescue plan in the form of financial assistance to the U.S. financial system worth <0x24>700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner).
But there is no victory yet.
Congress has to complete some of the details of the agreement before it can make public the final form of the law and its vote.
The draft financial system support will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the Financial Institutions Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
Senate officials say they will probably vote on the bill on Wednesday.
According to economists, there should be an announcement that the rescue plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor in revitalizing the financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, a "sobering up" occurs thereafter.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have taken a big step.
“We have resolved our differences of opinion on what the form of the market stabilization package should be,” said Democrat Nancy Pelosi.
He said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Lawmakers met with U.S. Secretary of the Treasury Henry Paulson on Saturday to give a final form to the government fund.
This should buy up the unsold mortgage assets of financial corporations, which put financial corporations at serious losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
“We are close to a final agreement on a draft that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
The remedial plan still needs to be continued, but I think we are there,” Paulson said.
Signal to Asian Trading
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling heavily.
Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada says lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement on Congress on Sunday.
This is intended to reassure investors before the start of trading on the Asian financial markets, where, due to the time zone, Congress could be the first to influence Monday’s trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of Congress will vote on the bill, nor is it clear whether the trial could be blocked at the last minute due to a problem.
The legislators hope that the law will be approved in the coming days.
However, the law is still undergoing a number of changes.
The total amount earmarked to assist the system shall be divided into two parts.
President George W. Bush said the first <0x24>350 billion should be made available as soon as possible.
However, Congress may block the release of the remaining amount, which is set at an additional <0x24>100 billion and later <0x24>350 billion, if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function.
Bush appreciates progress in negotiations
Although the President may veto this resolution, Congress may override its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program remained, which was to acquire assets for the purchase of bad mortgage securities that were losing their value, as hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to repay their mortgages.
“We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday,” Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President Bush is pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
Bush spokesman Tony Fratto said the president was “satisfied with Saturday’s progress and appreciated the bipartisan efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Restrictions on large redundancy payments
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Christopher Dodd, said the legislators had agreed on the responsibility for the financial program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the closure of discounts, and the timing of the financing draft.
The new law also restricts the so-called bussy redundancy payments of the directors participating in the programme and establishes a supervisory committee for the fund.
The fund should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on this and made great progress towards a deal that will work and benefit all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new instalments for the mortgages it purchases, with the aim of reducing the monthly instalments of debtors and allowing them to keep their houses.
Marek: Spiritual aid
According to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, the proposed draft is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"This is because it is not possible to know with what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be purchased.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government share their losses,” Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
According to Marek, it is not that important whether the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week.
“It is more important that Congress decide this week to support the plan and give its blessings as soon as possible.
The spiritual significance of reaching an agreement on the approval of the plan is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
Duel on blade: MP3 players vs. mobiles.
We help you choose
While almost all mobile devices can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can be used to make phone calls.
It seems clear from this that it is better to just buy a phone.
However, there are many reasons to purchase a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
You’ll probably have a hard time getting a high-end, expensive turntable to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc disc.
On the one hand, such music products do not appear on vinyl records, but there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues vinyl records, you’re probably dreaming of such a turntable.
This is similar to travel-destined, i.e. compressed - in short, MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to issue eight thousand crowns for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan would probably find it difficult to accept a 20-kroon market earphone.
There are two extremes between which there is enough room for everyone.
Wide choice.
The life of the batteries also matters
Some high-end music players can do much more than just play music, but also do what most mobile phones don’t even happen to do.
No device is as universal as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions of calling and texting, you can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera, and even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a small miracle, as no refrigerator can barbecue and no television can take photos.
Multi-functional mobile phones also have disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more the display sends to the charger.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, mostly much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
Therefore, with cheap mobile phones, you should expect that they will not play for you for more than a few hours.
If you’re even on the phone here and there, get another charger for your workplace just to be safe – this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players will not have this problem, even the worse ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with a single charge.
The next issue arises when uploading music to a mobile device.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB socket, and besides, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobile devices without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPods), players do not need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
Most mobile phones and players already create a music library sorted by the artist, album, genre name, or user rating, for example.
Some devices display only a tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, with a smart phone operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles know more
When choosing a specific device, inquire first of all about battery life, memory capacity, audio output quality and type, and of course, the convenience of handling.
If the music serves you primarily as a background and you only listen to it daily for a short period of time on the tram, for example, any mobile device that plays MP3 will be suitable for you.
This is something that any mobile phone can do.
You don’t even have to pay special attention to what music formats your mobile or player can do.
All of them will cope with MP3, and the vast majority of the music you receive will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most popular, and besides it, the vast majority of devices can handle WMA music as well.
AAC (the format used by Apple and for your iPod) is less common.
Better mobile phones also allow, for example, online music purchases.
It is enough to visit the appropriate pages of the provider (or other provider) via the mobile internet and purchase the song or album.
This service in itself can be a powerful argument for the purchase of a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of service providers is crappy and usually limited to annual radio hits.
Prices are not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that such a method of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you can scan your cell phone in your pocket while the forgotten MP3 player is at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least your hands-free hands-free.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which has almost all mobile, but only a few MP3 players.
For many, the biggest advantage of music mobiles will probably be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get a fair enough walkman.
However, you are mostly limited by the lack of the output of your traditional earphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones with traditional 3.5 mm hole headphones can cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
However, the advantages of the players are, among other things, their ease of use.
The simplest - by no means necessarily the cheapest players (see our selection) really cope with everyone.
Minimal functionality, handling similar to the previously standard cassette tape or gramophone is obvious.
There is no risk of a crash in the form of an accidentally turned on mobile internet, or a massive bill for data transmission that follows.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have slots for removable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
Buying the right card can cost up to 2,000 kroner.
But be careful.
Basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones know what to do with up to 8GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or irivet.
Based on the capacity (up to 2 GB), you don’t have to spend more than 1100 kronor.
If you belong to the more demanding students, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsungs).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, so the convenience of handling is closer to the MP3 player.
The Sony Ericsson, which has the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately, is the industry’s biggest success.
MP3 players of the aforementioned brands can offer the same service in the same price range up to four thousand kroons, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe...
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively developed and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual service provider that forces classic operators to substantially reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be for long.
On the Mobile.cz website we have written many times that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
Following the European Commission’s recent move to regulate roaming charges, this may lead to a controversial situation – texts sent from abroad to some of the Czech mobile operators’ customers will be cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple: there is no real competition.
This may sound contradictory, as we have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office, has often agreed with this, as he has previously stated several times that there is no room for a new operator in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the classical provider with its own network is unlikely to have too many chances (though it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is another option - the virtual service provider.
It was the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that brought about a significant price reduction, which the classic service providers also had to respond to.
Even before the big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, sounds like ours were heard in the UK.
However, it has been proven that such providers have their place and can really be successful.
However, we do not need to go too far for example.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than half a year, this service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider in the country.
In the meantime, Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which in the Czech Republic, among other things, owns U:fon.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the ability to focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, you need far fewer customers than a traditional service provider.
It does not involve relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers around the world tend to appear as low-cost – they offer cheap calls and SMS, which, however, are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers text messages at least 50 percent cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good bet to bet on a target group.
This company is specially focused on men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether an idea like the one in Poland can work for us.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, a spokesman for Vodafone, doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators claim
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not seem to be very hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it showed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not overly sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their utmost to avoid any potential competition.
The GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in the launch of the virtual service provider for some time now, which aims to take another step towards making Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesman.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information suggests that we may be lucky to have the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
His birth, however, is now surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not think that a full-featured virtual service provider has a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
Until now, we have not been approached by a unique subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of Telefónica 02 told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specific situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokeswoman for T-Mobile, exceptionally agrees with O2, adding: "To date, we have not recorded a single viable and bilaterally advantageous business project on which we could continue to build."
And he added, “In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will pop up.
At this moment, we should have a concrete agreement on our table so that we can think in such a short term.”
Vodafone focuses more on fulfilling its own 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, primarily in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most rewarding for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is partnering with the development of shared networks for high-speed mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - on the same line with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, and the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, a fall in prices and thus a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter?
When service providers are able to collaborate on something important, they testify to the long run around the birth of the U:phone.
The biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>TU was probably around the birth of the T-Mobile company’s U:phone.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on <0xC4><0x8C>TU’s website.
But right now, U:phone is a good reason why we shouldn’t allow the virtual service provider to log in.
Martina Kemrová added: “The environment of a competitor in the mobile market has recently been amplified by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be highly demanding.”
Given this attitude of mobile operators, however, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulators is astonishing.
In the meantime, it is not just the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no right to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries.
Only the Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the agency is characteristic of the whole problem.
“The entry of the virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider to lease the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contracts have been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for traditional service providers,” Kristián Chlapua, from the Foreign Relations Department of the Hungarian Competition Authority, said in response to our question.
A statement from the representatives of the service providers in this way would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the agency which should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one abuses his position on the market, this is more than odd.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas, where virtual service providers usually operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
However, it is likely that the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS do not include the pressure to ensure the proper functioning of the market environment and to reduce prices.
In this case, it is a shocking coherence that emerges from the reaction of the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is a coincidence is almost self-evident.
Just like at the filling stations, the exact same gasoline prices are surely the product of coincidence and fierce competition.
"The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a leading position, i.e. they have no proportionately greater responsibility for their market operations.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual service providers are probably lacking for the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said.
The presentation of market leadership is one of the many points of controversy.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>TU, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, there is no Czech operator in a leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
So in a certain segment it is necessarily dominant.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be a minimum warning to <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators behave strikingly similarly.
In the meantime, the complaints of interested parties (including GTS Novera, mentioned above) show that they face very similar obstacles in negotiating with all service providers.
The transfer of responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>TU is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS takes its hands off the whole matter.
We have seen this in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecoms Act, the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>TU’s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not carried out, although many experts hoped that the situation would improve.
Representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS should know this well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one is watching.
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of pseudo-virtual service providers, many of which are already operating on Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
They are multilevel marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The charm lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer against the provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a priority customer, you will then receive special quotes (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar advances.
"If there were any of the cases you are talking about, there would be a breach of contract that we would deal with and that could lead to the termination of cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová said in response to our question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that news of such activities would not have reached the responsible people of the mobile operators.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, there may be thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider will defend itself against such a procedure.
These companies have not negligible profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual service providers, they are not particularly threatening them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card is not in their name on their phones, so they cannot have it in full as general customers of mobile operators."
But at least that’s what the CTU should find strange.
In addition, there is another question that arises for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators are ignoring a similar procedure, why are they obstructing the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively strong powers to expose such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect anything of this kind and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As has already been stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has brought about a noticeable fall in the prices of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers have been established, classic service providers have tried to prevent them more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small or perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that regulators intervened, which in no way defended the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Then, either by formal measures or by informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider that others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are handing over the whole matter to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competencies are useful to them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may start moving again.
If one service provider would allow a virtual mobile service provider to be established, it is difficult for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And maybe we won't make phone calls more expensive than the rest of Europe.
