Prague transport company to deliver chip card for the first time on Wednesday
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, enter the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passenger enters the metro, tram and bus with an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper line ticket.
The coupon is currently available to around 100,000 people who have an Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day and annual coupon (valid as of 1 January 2009) and at the same time save it on their chip card at the information centres and offices of the Transport Company at Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE>í Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>l, Roztydok, Let<0xC5><0x88>any, Kobylisy, Rajskáh z.
Coupons can be purchased online from yesterday via the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers throughout the afternoon.
Those who start using the internet may forget the windows of the subway stations, where they have had to make long queues for line tickets on a regular basis.
The coupon can be purchased via the Internet and saved on the Opencard card in one of the City Library’s thirteen accounts.
“Passengers at these locations will have a counter with trained servers to help those interested to shop online and save their purchased vouchers to their cards,” said Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>, project spokesman.
In addition to libraries, electronic coupons can be saved on Opencard in the self-service vending machines installed in some lobbys.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket handlers and passengers may have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vlatavská metro stations.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty of them," Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD> added.
The coupon is checked automatically instead of the driver
Managing machines that start operating tomorrow is simple.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid coupon will be saved on its own.
From tomorrow, electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
So on the trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499, with which mainly residents of the districts of central Bohemia travel to the capital.
"In the integrated trains in Prague, the guides were equipped with card readers to determine the zone validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal of the Ropid organisation, which compiled the schedule for public transport in Prague.
In the buses around the city, card readers are installed by the driver at the checkout.
