Rats have emotions too.
A rat or a moth fleeing in danger. Does this mean that he feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals also have emotions.
But how can we see if they feel the same when they behave like us?
In the Internet magazine "Edge" famous scientists have published their articles for years.
In one of his series, SPIEGEL ONLINE looks at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of all human brains is the same.
However, as we look at other species and examine the questions of perception or consciousness in general, we come to a difficult terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: pretending to be dead, fleeing or attacking.
People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers infer comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
On the one hand, human consciousness-related circuits almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive/control functions).
This wide area is more highly developed in humans than in other primates, and appears to be completely absent in other organisms.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as the awareness of who we are, or the ability to plan and decide, it can reasonably be assumed that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since much of the human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not dependent on language, language would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might be like in other animals.
If consciousness is not measurable as an internal and subjective thing, and cannot be analyzed by our own experiences because of the special hardware, then his research puts us in serious trouble.
Most of my discussions are about the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The consciousness processes of animals could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments with short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, this assumption, which has been examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, relies more on the neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: Both can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What does this mean for the feelings?
I draw this back to the fact that an emotional system, like that of fear, is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies working memory.
In this way, emotions are closely related to the areas of the cerebral cortex that are characteristic of primates and humans in particular.
In addition to the linguistic character, perception is divided into subtle degrees, because with the help of words and grammar we are able to distinguish and categorize states, to describe them to others besides ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, for example, is of the opinion that emotions originate from simpler activities in the body’s perception areas of the cerebral cortex and brain stem, as is Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it can easily play a role in interspecies-wide emotions.
I cannot deny this purely theoretically, but I find it unprovable.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to be felt in both cases as well: How can we check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
