To overcome such performance gaps, Obama’s education plan explicitly supports – among other things – “transitional bilingual education” for English learners.
At the same time, for Obama, the question is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on non-English school education, outweighs his interest in overcoming the big performance gaps.
Take, for example, the Sixth Street Prep Contracted Primary School in the eastern part of Los Angeles County.
Most of the school’s students are Spanish-speaking and low-income.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently arrived, are learning English.
In spite of this, 100% of fourth graders achieved excellent results in the 2008 state mathematics exam.
Equally impressive is the fact that 93% of fourth graders passed the English Language and Literature exam.
This incredible achievement was not achieved by the means that Obama would prefer.
Sixth Street focuses on repetition, practice, constant evaluation of skills, and rejection of objections.
In addition, and this is what Obama should consider, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s educational principle is “total immersion” of English students into the language environment.
The essence of the immersion method is the almost exclusive use of English in the teaching of other subjects.
Mikels, who is opposed to bilingual education, said: “We’ve had overwhelming success in that if someone walked into a classroom, they wouldn’t realize who the student was who had just arrived from Mexico 12 months earlier.”
"It works," he said, "it works for us."
Would Obama set an example to be followed by schools such as Sixth Street Prep for other Spanish-speaking and English-speaking schools?
The school’s achievements should make the answer clear, but because of its party’s education policy (the National Education Associations have long supported bilingual education), and because of its own consistent advocacy of bilingual education, we cannot be sure of Obama’s reaction.
Although he agrees that immigrants should learn English, Obama recently underestimated the issue by saying that people should not be so worried about the “exclusive Englishness” of the legislation.
Instead, he said, "You should get your kids to speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to reduce the gaps in results, he should seriously study the models that work, rather than despise and ignore them.
