A Separate City, the Pride and Trials of Blacks
A few miles from everything that glitters, is loud and mighty, the Greater Orlando adventure park hides in a quiet little town where the pride and complexity of African-American life was born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city to integrate into the country and which was the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the five lakes, three croquet tracks, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guayavas and a city of two schools without prison."
It's a pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have attended the annual Zora Festival, which is a celebration of the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance, Hurston.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction, which is also included in the Florida guide published by the Crisis Age Federal Writers Project, is distinct from its surroundings.
As independent, dignified, and closed-minded as it was in the 1930s, Hurston wrote that urban blacks in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with white people who “know so little about us that they don’t know what they’re missing.”
Even in the year when Black presidential candidate Barack Obama encourages an open debate on the race issue, many here are mistrusting the eyes of outsiders.
“We are very careful about how our story is told,” said 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here all her life and is a member of the city’s oldest church.
"You have to tell it right."
Eatonville has long been characterized by a paradox of victory and struggle.
It is a historically significant model of black’s stance, but it is also a community of almost 2,400 people, where poverty rates double the national average.
It is partly a literary hub and partly an example of the sometimes despised, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture that flourishes in the shade of oak trees.
It is not surprising, then, that the people here are proud and defensive at the same time.
The image of Eatonville has been important since Zora (here everyone calls Hurston that).
In books written in sincere, strong dialect, such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937), he introduced his hometown to the world.
Five paragraphs in the Florida guidebook transformed the city, which is located next to Route 17. This road leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave in life and literature like a drum, introduced his readers to Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke's business, and then looked into the more intimate spheres.
To the right of the road, we find a modern public school with a white border on a brown background, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds maintained by Howard Miller, although he can barely read or write.
He mentioned the widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and whatever you may need in transitional shelters."
Thus, in a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to autonomy, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Obviously, the Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
Not everyone really liked this description.
"Zora said things the way they were," said Ella Dinkins, a 90-year-old Johnson girl. Hurston made them immortal by quoting the slippery songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added, “Some people didn’t like that.”
Hurston is still remembered here as a living stranger who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived without notice in a rumbling Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and wearing long pants to a city where people still pride themselves on their dignified dress.
"Most people were fascinated," Franklin said, "but many were delighted."
"People were always happy to see Zora," Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair: "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were never published again.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with much of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although once a popular writer, Langston Hughes' contemporary, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
In Eatonville there were no significant memorials or large public readings.
"I don't think they understood how much it enriched the world, or what it left behind at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of the 2003 Hurston biography, "Wrapped in a Rainbow."
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road through the city instead of the two-lane main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in community life.
The expansionist Orlando has already penetrated the state-connected Interstate 4 motorway on the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering after a difficult period in history.
Among other things, forced integration put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the struggles with racial mixing brought hatred to the community.
"A group of white boys came over at the time and threw oranges and other things at those on the side of the road," Franklin said.
"There was a lady who died in this.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's decision to impose forcibly integration, stating that Brown v. Board of Education was "a violation of my race rather than a respect for it."
Today, residents say that school segregation, although positive in some respects, weakened the cohesion of the people of eatonville and undermined the self-confidence of young people.
"Black kids are used to being hugged -- I remember that -- a man hugged his teacher in the morning and in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins' daughter, executive director of the nonprofit organization "Guard the Community of Eatonville."
"This took as long as the students and teachers came from a common place," he added.
"We didn't hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher -- I mean, there were cultural differences between us," Nathiri said.
However, human rights helped the rise of many other Zora Neale Hurston – black writers, actors and artists who have risen above prejudices, as she did, with as optimistic self-confidence and lines as: “How can anyone deprive themselves of the enjoyment of my company!
This is incomprehensible to me.”
In 1975, Alice Walker made a pilgrimage to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to restore her reputation.
Five years later, a renowned Hurston biography, written by Robert E. Hemenway, was placed on the shelves of bookshops, once again placing him among America’s role models.
The road construction project was about to begin when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the spotlight.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
In 1988, the community started organizing a Hurston festival to show what the county would ruin with its main road.
Thousands of fans attended the opening event two years later, and since then many have returned to the ceremony every January.
A few years later, the county withdrew from its road construction proposal.
“Due to the five lanes of the main road, the community has been revived, turned to full speed, which is a real civic pride,” Nathiri said.
Boyd put it simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road construction project helped to change the city’s image of itself.
An increasing number of outsiders, such as Rachelle Munson, who began attending church in 1993, began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was included in the National Historical List in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) opened on Kennedy Avenue, which was re-encrusted and embellished.
Eatonville remained the cuckoo egg of Florida: not quite ten kilometers from the center of Orlando, but sometimes it feels like a suburban side street during summer rain; as small as when it was founded in the 1880s by 27 black families.
(Ninety percent of the population is black.)
They are still cautious with the outsiders who come here in search of the story of Eatonville.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things — such as Eatonville’s oldest fresco, painted by a white man and depicting blacks working in the fields — should not be photographed.
In Eatonville, many—including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly attracted to bright red—are afraid that their separate community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival became more widespread, the pride of the hometown also grew.
Young people in particular view Eatonville more and more as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with his problems and everything, neither better nor worse, as proud, as creative, as diligent, as foolish and confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
Franklin’s 18-year-old nephew, Edwin Harvey, is planning on returning to college to work for the local government or the police, who he believes need help.
And it seems younger people have learned to describe Eatonville correctly, like the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most of those who are just passing through here think this city is nothing compared to the rest," Alondra Kenon said recently after the church service on a Sunday.
“But if you stop and take some time to get to know your history, it’s a very beautiful city.”
