“I don’t take photographs on stage because I want to introduce the artist from a personal perspective.” – Günther Bauer, Photographer
No sets, no curls, no dancing shoes.
The grand masters of flamenco, without the excitement of the performance: to get to know the everyday faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the ordinary man.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in the intimate moments away from the audience, when we can pass through a personal gesture, grasp the depth of a captured look, or marvel at the beauty of the idle but expressive hand of the artist who is preparing to perform outside the stage.
The German photographer Günther Bauer’s series Flamenco-people combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this less well-known everyday side of the masters.
Through the photos, the flamenco’s unique iconography is presented from different perspectives.
The exhibition, which is part of the Month of Flamenco Photography, “reflects the growing international significance of flamenco every day,” says the creator, adding that the Flamenco-people “can be anyone, as the viewer realizes that these images represent artists in a non-typical way.
These people who are photographed on the streets are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivate the audience.
Stage photography, however, is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character dwell in the depths of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the great flamenco players with the help of the camera.”
The Cante de las Minas festival inspired Bauer's long journey in 1997, during which he took portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a disc camera.
These portraits evoke classical photography thanks to the camera and the choice of subject.
However, the use of different stylistic tools breaks with traditional visual representations and suggests modernity. The following thought faithfully reflects Bauer's vision of flamenco: "This is music with traditional roots, but it is changing day by day and always fascinating."
It is not the dance, nor the song or the music in itself, but rather the personality and character of the artist that enchants the audience.
The main motive of the works to be viewed in the El Fotomata gallery these days is the search for an encounter with the essence, the artistic varász, which becomes visible through the way of perception, being and representation.
Famous flamenco figures include Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others.
The project has also become a flamenco anthology, which will soon be the subject of an album featuring portraits presented at the exhibition.
Two years ago, Bauer’s passion for portraits inspired him to repeat the idea with the series “Portraits of Veteran Athletes” (“SportARTproject”).
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is slightly different, the photographer adds: "I really like to photograph people, get to know them and enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is portraits.
You meet people, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know, people you don’t know.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.
Selected from contemporary flamenco portraits, the exhibition entitled Flamenco-people can be viewed in the El Fotomata Gallery, located at the parallel of the Alameda de Hércules at the number 20 of the Calle de la Mata, until 16 October.
