Those Who Speak in Dreams
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean the ones who wake up and fully awake and tell what happened to them that day, but the ones who talk while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem frightening at first, but it is actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquism.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure many of you have been told that you spoke at night.
Its frequency can be completely rapsodic (for example, it occurs only once in a high fever illness) or more regular (every day, weekly or monthly), and usually the next day the child does not remember anything.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single cause.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night awakenings, enuresis nocturna or sleepwalking, but this is not legal.
As mentioned above, a condition with high fever, or even a stress or an increased state of excitement, may be accompanying phenomena.
It has been little studied so far.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It can be quiet, calm, consisting of inconsistent words, murmuring, but in contrast, it can also manifest itself in the form of shouting, crying, or prolonged speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist. The examination may reveal whether there is a problem that is causing great anxiety and thus it may offer a solution.
As already mentioned, it is a benign phenomenon, and consequently, there is no cure for it unless it is associated with another form of sleep disorder that can be treated (such as insomnia or stress).
However, there are a few things you can do, here are some preventive measures:
