The blood is safe again.
President Dr Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate today, because Héma-Quebec has become one of the safest and most effective blood donors in the world.
And most importantly, he managed to regain people’s trust, which was severely shattered by the 1980s and 1990s contaminated blood scandal.
As is well known, national blood reserves managed by the Blood Service of the Red Cross of Canada were infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general upheaval, in February 1994, the Canadian government, led by Judge Horace Krever, launched a formal investigation to clarify the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to formulate recommendations to avoid similar incidents in the future.
While Judge Krever delayed the submission of his report, some provinces set up their own committees to design a new blood treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee was responsible for this task.
The Gelineau and Krever reports resulted in the establishment of two blood supply services in Canada: the Hema-Quebec, which serves Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Supply Society, which is responsible for supplying all the other provinces and two territories.
“When Hema-Quebec began its operations in 1998, less than 38% of people had confidence in Quebec’s blood supply system,” Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was desperate.
"In the following years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, we were able to regain people's confidence." Décary proudly announces that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the population of Quebec already considered Hema-Quebec to be trustworthy.
Dr. Décary, however, does not forget that “trust is an extremely fragile thing.”
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has applied the principle of caution.
It was during this period that many cases of goose disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were discovered in Europe, says the doctor, who has been in charge of the company since its founding in 1998.
"We had no idea if this disease was transmitted by blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are unsure about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we need to apply exclusion measures. In this case, we were talking about Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain lesions, thus inevitably leading to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
And a few years ago, there was no doubt that the disease was spreading through blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the principle of caution."
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that makes it possible to diagnose HIV more sensitively. This is a nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to detect the virus itself directly in the blood of blood donors, rather than the antibodies that were formed against the virus, on which the tests used earlier were based.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which takes from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood with the help of our technical equipment, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, they significantly reduced the risk of unknowingly infecting the bloodstream by blood donors and preventing it from being detected.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of spreading AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
In other words, it means that we need to distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone would become infected with HIV through a blood product.
I believe that anyone can now safely accept or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health, says the head of Hema-Quebec.
“The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
You never know what kind of new pathogen will enter the system.
After all, it was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood by insect bites.
Therefore, we must be constantly on the lookout,” Dr. Décary continued, stressing that, in addition to emergency reserves, Hema-Quebec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
“With the ageing of the population, demands are increasing.
Because cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has an impact on the blood donor population, as the number of people eligible for blood donation in the network accounts for only 3% of the population of Quebec.
However, every healthy person aged at least 18 years who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have been to a country where malaria is devastating do not have the right to donate blood for a year.
“We have 3% reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It is very rare that we run out of supplies.
The number of blood donors, on the other hand, must be increased as the existing ones age, because after a while they will no longer be able to donate blood.
However, it is very difficult to persuade people to donate blood, but it is even more difficult to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
“In today’s fast-paced world, you have barely an hour to go and donate blood,” Francine Décary said.
With an annual budget of <0x24>297 million, Héma-Quebec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin tissue, which is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen, and then deposited at the Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public stem cell bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, once treated only as medical waste, can be used to extract blood that is rich in stem cells, thus allowing for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago that we received the 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample in our bank, and we plan to take more than 1,000 new samples every year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering these for organ transplants,” explained Dr. Décary, who says that the umbilical cord blood collection program is very popular nowadays.
"Many mothers are saddened that they don't have the opportunity to do this," this is indeed the case, as Hema-Quebec is not in a position to make this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
