The Psychology of Overbidding: Why Do We Spend More Money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neurological-economic foundations of this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by researchers from the University of New York in neuroscience and economics.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose out in a type of competition like eBay’s auction, so they tend to pay too high a price.
The study attempted to map the neurological scheme of this "play" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers took part in a lottery and the other group participated in a game auction while using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to study the active brain areas of the subjects.
Both games allowed participants to win money, but during the auction game, in which an essential element is the overbidding of the other party, the subcortical complex called striatum became active intensively when the game was lost.
This area of the brain, among many other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price rise can be explained by avoiding a violent reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economist members of the research group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this, three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product in question was, and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they got out of the game, they would be rewarded with an additional <0x24>15.
The third group received <0x24>15 just before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, the members of the group also lost that money.
The only difference between the two groups was that they emphasized winning for one group and losing for the other.
Proving the neurologists' hypothesis, however, the members of the team playing "against loss" were willing to bet higher than both the control and the "winning" groups.
"These results cannot be derived from any existing economic theory.
So far, they have only explained the phenomena of the auction with the joy of winning and risk avoidance.
Only neurological imaging techniques have helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories, so that we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of people infected with hepatitis at home is estimated to be 100,000, but only seven thousand are being treated, which is why patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a common name for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
Their symptoms have many similarities, are characterized by hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses are transmitted in two main forms: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tract (for example, with infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D, and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travellers should be protected by vaccination against A and B viruses, but there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, nausea.
After this, yellowing appears on the skin and whites of the eyes, the stools are light, the urine turns dark, healing can take two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis, liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the cells of the liver, in many cases the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to carry out early prevention and regular screening tests.
Three groups have significantly more than average cases of this disease: people who had had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and people who had tattoos.
The number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is estimated at 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory test, if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected, it is worth consulting a general practitioner.
When the disease is detected in time, it can be cured, the virus can be eradicated from the body, thus eliminating the infectivity and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, which was first held in 2004 by organisations representing patients around the world.
It aims to raise awareness of chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
If you believe in God, it hurts less.
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a kind of painkiller, which may have eased the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment to investigate how God-belief affects people’s perception of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
In the rather bizarre study, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were electrocuted while all of them were studying a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to exclude much of the pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for controlling pain.
The study is the first in a series of research involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The study was carried out precisely by attaching a sparkling device to the subject's left hand, which provided the electroshock.
The researchers asked the participants to look vigorously at two paintings, The Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and The Lady with Hermelin painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would create a kind of religious state among believers, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive episodes while either watching the religious theme or the overall picture.
The Catholics reported that during the sight of the Virgin Mary they felt "safe" as if they were "cared for" and "calmed, filled with peace."
When viewing a religious-themed picture, they reported 12 percent less pain than when they saw Leonardo’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who participated in the study himself, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, even in atheists, just the right photo should be found.
"We should find a picture of someone who feels very positively about them, like a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the search.
“The practice of faith should and in many cases does change our personality,” Wright added.
After the great results, the only question is, if Leonardo, or a painter of a similar caliber, showed the believers a picture of a Madonna, what effect would that have on their pain control?
Would the sight of the quality of the Virgin Mary mean even better results?
