The flight of the bumblebee is imitated by the intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop collision avoidance technologies, if not by imitating obstacle detectors that occur in the natural world?
Bees, for example.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the dwarf bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C, a bio-imitation automotive robotic control system, a robotized mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to design a system that eliminates all collisions.
"While flying, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective shell," Kazuhhiro Doi, head of technology PR and R&D brand, explained at the exhibition.
The role of the complex eye of the uterus is important, which can see in all directions at an angle of view of more than 300 degrees.
To replicate the complex eye function, the engineers turned to the idea of a laser telemeter.
It identifies obstacles within a distance of 2 meters at 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which immediately converts into a collision avoidance operation.
The obstacle is detected in a fraction of a second, and the car robot immediately changes direction by turning its wheels as much as is necessary to avoid a collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver is carried out entirely instinctively.
“If this were not the case, the car-robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
You need to react in an inspiring and immediate way, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety protective shell, a layer within which a collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should take place in the blink of an eye.
However, in a way other than bees, the deviation cannot be upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the turnability of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities available to bees to bypass other bees, only rotary motion and acceleration, as well as deceleration, were used here as available options for the car robot.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer service life than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, the instinctive intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process data, even less the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so you will constantly use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of an immediate evasion technology, which Nissan estimates will enter production within ten years.
Additional applications include integrating the unit with the GPS-satellite navigation system to drive the driver to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
