Domestic sales prices of industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, reports the HCSO.
The prices of industrial export sales were 1.1 per cent higher than in July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
As a result of the domestic and export price changes, industrial producer prices were 0.7 per cent higher than in the previous month and 3.2 per cent higher than a year earlier.
Domestic sales prices of industry increased only 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors also increased slightly by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The biggest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), mainly due to a 4.6 per cent increase in the monthly price of bags and straps, and a 2.5% increase in the monthly price of footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6%).
Prices fell in the sectors of petroleum processing (1.4%), electrical machinery and instrumentation (0.9%) and - to a minimum extent - wood processing (0.1%).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
In other manufacturing sectors, we measured price increases between 0.2% and 0.9%.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which have a significant weight in the domestic sales of industry, increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the transient effect of the official gas price increase implemented from 1 July.
Prices in the petroleum processing sector increased the most in terms of domestic sales in the manufacturing sector (32.4%) compared to the twelve-month period.
In the manufacturing of metal products, the price of food, beverages and tobacco, representing the dominant weight, rose by 13.2 percent and 11 percent respectively.
