The European Equal Opportunities Summit, which this year is hosted by the French Presidency of the European Union, has begun today in Paris.
Lívia Járóka, the Fidesz MEP of the European People’s Party, in her message to the plenary as one of the main speakers of the professional conference, drew attention to educational segregation, as this is one of the most serious violations affecting Roma children, and it is also the most serious obstacle to their enforcement.
The high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities, on behalf of the French Presidency.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and the most important European human rights defenders and NGOs in the field of equal opportunities were invited to the meeting.
