"The vast majority of Roma young people do not have a secondary education and only a minority of them have access to higher education because of poor basic education."
Járóka also stressed that, as a fundamental human right, education plays a key role in the enforcement of other human rights.
Investing in early childhood education for Roma children can help to strengthen the economies of the EU Member States.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these connections in the widest range - also among Roma and non-Roma.
The sooner a Roma student starts school, the more their chances of becoming productive members of the labour market increase; they contribute to the national budget through taxes on income and consumption.
“Roma must have the right to a quality education on the basis of their European citizenship, and the elimination of their low quality and segregated education must be guaranteed,” Lívia Járóka stressed.
