The Elite in Danger
The phenomenon was already felt a few days ago, when the House of Representatives did not vote for the <0x24>700 billion rescue package presented by the White House: a significant proportion of Americans were more interested, and still are, in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which reports that the current crisis has resulted in a break within the Republican Party that shows an increasing division between the traditional, restrained Eastern coastal attitude in support of federal institutions and business circles and the ever-increasing new anti-Washington and anti-financial world stance in the central and southern states.
This line was critically expressed in the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
The above event, however, is only one of the major changes that the ongoing economic rearrangement foreshadows or allows us to see, not only in the United States, but in the entire Western world, and perhaps beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is only accelerating the phenomena that have been latent for a long time and that are consolidating in this new atmosphere and finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is the re-actualization, the re-establishment of a double category of state sovereignty, in connection with a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis affects those banking and financial institutions which, while having close links with the rest of the world, are primarily and on a fairly wide scale attracting people and families living in a single country, a single state.
This, on the other hand, presents a direct political difficulty for those in government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also voters.
Thus, the crisis seems to be global in economic terms, but it is almost exclusively national in political terms.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially out of bounds: the European Union, which is unable to define a unified political line between different interests and different national strategies, is a fine example of this.
So everyone expects intervention, a rescue package, a revival and new rules from the individual national governments, but most importantly, the opening of funds: because in a difficult situation, only the individual states have economic resources, financial resources that can make things right.
They also have the means and the authority to use them: they have two invaluable resources in certain circumstances that no other market or international organisation will ever possess to such an extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on nation-statehood is fully in line with the fact that economic growth in recent times has given increasing importance to a factor closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we were entering the abstract world of the grid, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, and that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we suddenly realized that our future was increasingly dependent on things that were not so abstract as water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one half of the planet to the other, yet they are wholly related to a limited place, an area.
So whoever controls the area has a lot more cards than someone who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
This brings me to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fault line.
He who says territory, state, government, must also say: politics, in other words, leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to produce two intertwined phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, someone who can handle events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially the economic leaders, who have proven to be completely incompetent and have shown that much of the obscurity lies ahead.
The two together are of even deeper significance and, in a sense, more disturbing: a feeling of loss of trust, impatience, inadequacy and segregation that affects the entire leadership elite in an increasing number of Western countries.
It seems, therefore, that there is a growing belief among the population that the time of the social elite, which has hitherto peaked, is over. It has expired before they have embraced their actions, experiences, lifestyles, cultures, in the complex sense of the word. With this, the social elite is increasingly alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In a word, the need for leadership, in a veiled form, fuels a diverse but strong movement of delegitimation against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This is manifested in the unexpected "revolts" of voters, or in recent sudden changes in the anti-Italian mood. For example, the rise to power of conservatives in Congress in Austria and Bavaria, the unity of Labour in Britain.
It seems that the traditional elite, with its parties, programs, and even its renowned intellectuals, together with its habits, press and intellectuals, understands less and less and less what has been happening in the deeper strata of Western society for some time.
Despite all this, it would be an exaggeration to speak of “the imminent revolt of the masses.”
