Goodbye old Cinema Paradiso, the time of the old cinemas in the cities has passed
Traditional cinemas are closing in favor of Multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
The pictures, taken by director Giuseppe Tornatore, impressively illustrate what is happening in Italy’s big cities, but also in rural regions.
The displacement of cinemas - the appearance of large, multi-room cinemas in the suburbs and the subsequent decay of single-room cinemas in the city centers - is a process that seems inevitable and irreversible, but at the same time carries all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
When historic and memorable places disappear, "it's like having a friend go away, a friend with whom we shared our journey and many experiences," says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which twenty years ago won an Oscar, as well as the Grand Prix of the Cannes Festival, probably lost to Tornatore.
The largest association of operators, Anec, has reported that 316 traditional cinemas have closed in the last five years. The biggest losses were recorded by cinemas in major cities: 10 cinemas in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Emilia-Romagna leads among the most affected regions, losing 82 one-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And that the proliferation of multiplexes is responsible for their disappearance is no better evidence than the fact that Italy has the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions: in the last five years the number of rooms has increased by 195 in Lombardy, by 81 in Tuscany and by the same number in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says Anec president Paolo Protti. "Okay, we are building new facilities, but the survival of those that already exist should also be ensured, because when a city cinema closes, not all those who go there are willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the unfunded funds intended to support operators: the State’s overdue debt is estimated at around EUR 10 million.
It is disgraceful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government is not complying with the legislation in force.
It would take between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million a year to maintain the market.”
The case of Bologna deserves special attention. It is the first Italian city to decide, in its concern about closures, to remedy the problem by means of an agreement between the municipality and Anec in order to protect and boost the single-room cinemas in the outer and downtown areas.
The provisions would include tax advantages for operators and benefits for the public in terms of accessibility: spectators can enter restricted zones and park at a reduced rate in certain parking lots.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna, even by introducing other measures.
But it’s also certain that traditional cinemas need to improve sound and image quality to be able to fight multiplexes, because today’s audience is much more demanding.
The preservation of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of Supercinema in Bagheria, where I spent my childhood and adolescence, gave me the spark that made me finally make Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, so when I go on the Via Nazionale in front of the closed Rialto or Quirinale to avoid seeing the blackened posters of the dust, I turn my head. I have had so many experiences here."
Close ties between politics and 'ndrangheta, Gioia Tauro's mayor arrested
“The mayor of Gioia Tauro supported the interests of the Piromalli clan in municipal decisions.”
Judges of the Anti-Mafia Directorate in Calabria have made serious accusations against Gioia Tauro, Mayor and Deputy Mayor, Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, as well as Rosarno Mayor Carlo Martelli, who were arrested this morning on charges of external involvement in a criminal network.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the senior mediator between the clan and the administration, and his nephew, a lawyer of the same name, who had previously been convicted of participating in a mafia-like crime network, were also handcuffed and charged with <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>10 million in damages.
"Disregard of all legal and moral rules, even of good taste," state prosecutors write. The two local governments have declared their intention to pay counseling fees to lawyer Piromalli.
"Then the clan would have officially had access to the town hall, which would have given additional opportunity to control and manage the administration, which is already significant.
Agazio Loiero, president of the General Assembly of the region of Calabria, does not hide that there is “many collusion between the local institutions and the organized underworld” in the region: There are areas where the spread of the mafia is stronger than elsewhere, where collusion is almost inevitable.
Many local politicians, however, resist the pressure of the 'ndrangheta, they are the heroes who remain clean."
The arrests this morning are a sequel to the events of July, when the police announced that they had succeeded in decapitating the Piromalli clan.
At the end of April, local politicians were relieved of their mandate to administer the municipality. Gioia Tauro's municipal committee was dissolved once in 1991, even then due to alleged interconnections between organised crime and the local government.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, the Christian Democratic mayor who reigned in the dissolution, took the lead of the centre-right coalition in the second round of 2006.
He shouted a scandal when the County House ordered the dissolution of the municipal committee.
The then deputy interior minister Marco Minnini has been tried and accused of planning everything for political reasons, but the court said in a warrant signed this morning that the Piromalli clan had ventured to demand a change to the A3 project.
The interception ordered against Dal Torrione reveals, state prosecutors write, that "he was willing to comply with the demands of an extensive entrepreneur representing a group known to be close to the Piromalli family, and to subordinate the local government's decisions to the interest of the clan."
The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones are coming
An inexhaustible source of energy that accounts for 70% of the planet’s surface and is only now being discovered by major international energy companies.
Waves, sea currents, tides, all renewable energy sources that giants like Chevron are now trying to put their hands on.
For hundreds of years, they've been looking for ways to get energy from the motions of the sea, and in the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research intensified.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of exploiting offshore energy was put aside, but today the demands of environmental protection and the re-elevation of oil prices are giving the industry a new impetus.
The London World Energy Council (WEC) estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by installations that use sea waves.
That’s twice as much as is currently being produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
Giants are on the move.
Enersis was the first company to commit itself to offshore energy and in 2005 signed an agreement to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
It seemed a revolutionary move when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed, and more and more companies are opting for offshore energy, including those who have been committed to traditional energy so far.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies and is considering working with us," a spokesman for an associated oil giant, the Wall Street Journal, said in a statement.
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit issued by the US Energy Commission to launch a project in Alaska to exploit offshore energy.
This is of no small importance, especially considering that the US is currently extracting oil in Alaska, and President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power are also on the path of offshore energy. The amounts invested so far, as far as the details are concerned, show a growing interest.
Technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, this is still a rudimentary technology, just because the energy from the sea does not dispel the doubts about the environmental impact.
The existing installations, such as those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small in size and therefore do not pose a major problem for the ecosystem.
In order to produce energy on a larger scale, however, it is necessary to have installations with a greater environmental impact.
There are several options: for example, Ocean Power uses an interconnected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves that move the buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure rotates a turbine, which feeds a generator.
Electricity flows through cables under the sea to land.
There are currently four similar facilities in the planning phase, which are only awaiting federal permits. Some of the energy generated would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started generating energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines located in the East River Strait in New York.
During a tide, the movement of water rotates the blades of the turbines, and this rotating movement feeds the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are only waiting for permits to use the energy.
Waves after tides.
At present, special attention should be paid to the opportunities that can be exploited through tides.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and can therefore be considered a more reliable source of energy.
